Transforming variable date


avocado <- avocado %>% 
  mutate(date = ymd(date),
         month_enter = month(date, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE),
         year_enter = year(date),
         day_enter = day(date),
  )
avocado <- avocado %>% 
  mutate(quarters = case_when(
    month_enter %in% c('January','February','March')~ "Q1",
    month_enter %in% c('April','May', 'June') ~ "Q2",
    month_enter %in% c('July','August','September') ~ "Q3",
    month_enter %in% c('October', 'November', 'December')~ "Q4",
  ))
avocado

The first interpretation of this plot suggest a strong statistical significance between the average price of avocados with year, any kind of size and total volume.But the correlation is weak even if it is positive or negative.Also, this correlation depends if the origin of the avocado is ‘conventional’ or ‘organic’. If the type is organic the average price is sensible higher than conventional in any quarter of the year, specially in the third one(July- September). The strong significant relationship and the better correlation is between the total_volume and the avocado sells by size x4046, x4225, x4770 overall in conventional but also in the organic type The negative correlation could be interpreted as the average_price of avocados decrease as the total number of avocados available (in the market) increase.

A linear model about the relation of the average_price of avocado with all the variable from data set shows that with a positive correlation are year, region ( no all of them),the organic type and finally, size.

First predictor Average_price- year

model1 <- lm(average_price ~ year, data = avocado_trim2)

As it was mentioned before, there is a significant relationship between year and average_price. However, r-square point out that only a 0.8% in the variance of the average_price is based in year; the Residual standard error is 0.4 on - I think- to high degrees of freedom, that indicates the average error on predicting the average price is 0.4.

Plot model1

par(mfrow = c(2,2))

plot(model1)

The Residuals vs Fitted plot looks strange because there is no a well variation (I would say no well sorted). It makes me think in a variation by quarters, the same for the rest plots where the variation is to vertical. By contrast, I would say the the Q-Q plot is correct with a normal distribution.
